Executive Summary
Langford, British Columbia (population 58,320; 5.0% annual growth), lacks a centralized facility for accessible, hands-on STEM education [1]. While the University of Victoria (approximately 22,000 students) and Camosun College (approximately 19,000 learners) provide institutional lab access, these resources are restricted to enrolled students during designated hours. The Victoria Makerspace, the region’s primary alternative, operates on an application-based membership model with limited hours and a narrow disciplinary focus [16]. Crossroads Community STEM Centre addresses this gap by providing open-access, beginner-friendly programming across four focused disciplines: Robotics and Electronics, Digital Fabrication, Software Development, and Creative Design.
The facility will operate on a drop-in model with tiered staffed hours (~63 supervised hours per week across seven days) and sliding-scale fees. All participants complete a mandatory 30-minute safety orientation before accessing equipment, satisfying WorkSafeBC requirements [11] while maintaining a low barrier to entry. The facility provides equitable access to tools regardless of income or affiliation.
The project requires a first-year startup investment of $359,950 (lean, 4,000 sqft) to $577,300 (expanded, 6,000 sqft), indexed to current Langford commercial lease rates of $16 to $22 per square foot net plus Triple Net (NNN) costs. Long-term sustainability is achieved through diversified revenue, with no single funding source exceeding 30 percent of total income, and a projected transition to 55 percent earned revenue by Year 3. A break-even analysis (Table 4) demonstrates that monthly revenue targets exceed operating costs, with the surplus designated for the 15 percent contingency reserve. I request your review and approval of this proposal to begin the institutional partnership and funding acquisition phases.






