4. Risk Mitigation and Sustainability Plan
4.1 Risk Mitigation Strategy
Project implementation involves several critical risks requiring proactive management:
Facility Delay: If a facility partnership is not secured within the first three months, Crossroads will adopt a “pop-up” model, renting community center space for mobile workshops while continuing permanent lease negotiations.
Funding Shortfall: If grant funding is lower than projected, the project will scale to the lean budget of $359,950. Initial offerings will prioritize high-demand disciplines (Robotics and Software Development) and expand as revenue allows.
Low Participation: If attendance targets are not met, the Program Director will reallocate the marketing budget toward free trial workshops and direct partnerships with School Districts 61, 62, and 63.
4.2 Long-term Sustainability Plan
Financial independence is central to long-term viability. Revenue will be generated through multiple channels: workshop fees, monthly memberships, equipment surcharges, corporate training contracts, event hosting, and grant funding. To protect against the loss of any single income stream, no individual funding source (such as a government grant or corporate sponsor) exceeds 30 percent of total revenue. Earned revenue, defined as the aggregate of memberships, workshop fees, equipment surcharges, corporate training, and event hosting, is projected to reach 55 percent of total income by Year 3. This target is consistent with the 30 percent cap because earned revenue comprises multiple distinct sub-categories, each individually below the threshold.
