5. Evaluation Plan
Success will be measured through quantitative metrics tracked on a quarterly basis:
Engagement Analytics: Number of active monthly participants and average hours on-site. Year 1 targets: 150 unique participants per quarter and a 40 percent return rate. Year 3 targets: 500 participants per quarter and a 60 percent return rate.
Employment Pipelines: Growth of student internship placements and member career transitions into technical roles.
Social Impact Data: Member surveys tracking self-reported improvements in well-being, skill confidence, and community connectivity.
Health and Well-Being Programming: In partnership with local organizations, Crossroads will offer complementary programming including stress relief workshops and peer support groups. Anonymized survey data will measure the hub’s contribution to participant well-being and support grant applications focused on community health outcomes.
Institutional Partnerships: A minimum of four annual partnerships with local schools and businesses to sustain programming.
6. Conclusion and Action Statement
Crossroads Community STEM Centre addresses a documented gap in Langford’s infrastructure: the absence of an open-access facility where residents can develop practical technical skills without post-secondary enrollment. With a population growing at 5.0 percent annually and no comparable local facility, the demand for accessible STEM education is supported by both regional growth data and resident survey feedback (Appendix F) [1]. The tiered operating model, focused on four core disciplines and 63 staffed hours per week, aligns the project’s scope with its budget and staffing capacity.
The first-year investment of $359,950 to $577,300 reflects current Langford lease rates and realistic equipment costs. The diversified revenue strategy, validated through the break-even analysis in Table 4, provides a clear path to financial sustainability by Year 3: monthly revenue of $34,000 against $30,000 in operating costs generates a $4,000 surplus that self-funds the contingency reserve. Institutional partnerships with Camosun College and the University of Victoria, combined with the VIATEC corporate network, establish the foundation for long-term community impact.
